{"title_page": "Halloway (EP)", "text_new": "{{Infobox EP|\n| name         = Halloway\n| type         = EP\n| artist       = [[Tessa Violet]]\n| cover        = Halloway_EP_cover.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = September 16, 2016\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length       = 16:51\n| label        = \n| producer     = Seth Earnest\n| prev_title   = [[Maybe Trapped Mostly Troubled]]\n| prev_year    = 2014\n| next_title   = Bad Ideas (Act One)\n| next_year    = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Halloway''''' is a 2016 [[Extended play|EP]] by American musician [[Tessa Violet]]. It was released on September 16, 2016 on [[Compact disc|CD]].<ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\" />\n\n== Background ==\nThe title of ''Halloway'' was inspired by the character Will Halloway from the novel ''[[Something Wicked This Way Comes (novel)|Something Wicked This Way Comes]]'' by [[Ray Bradbury]]. Violet listened to [[audiobook]] version while on [[concert tour|tour]] after her mom said it was \"one of the scariest books she\u2019s read, and one of the most well-written.\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> Violet described the album as \"dark pop\".<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n''Halloway'' was released in 2016.<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Hull 2019\" /> Seth Earnest, who has worked with Tessa Violet since 2013, produced the album.<ref name=\"Cline 2019\" /><ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n== Production ==\nDuring ''Halloway''{{'}}s production, Violet listened to [[Taylor Swift]]'s ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]'', [[Troye Sivan]]'s ''[[Blue Neighbourhood]]'', and [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]'s ''[[Badlands (Halsey album)|Badlands]]''; as well as [[pop music|pop]] [[playlist]]s on [[Spotify]].<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n== Alternate versions ==\nViolet released a [[royalty-free]] [[A-side and B-side|B-Side]]s version through her second reward tier of her [[Patreon]].<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = \n| headline        = \n| title1          = Dream\n| length1         = 3:26\n| title2          = Not over You\n| length2         = 3:13\n| title3          = Haze\n| length3         = 3:46\n| title4          = On My Own\n| length4         = 2:56\n| title5          = I Don't Get to Say I Love You Anymore\n| length5         = 3:30\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n''CelebMix.com''{{'}}s Annemarie Cutruzula favoured ''Halloway'' with \"a collection of five fresh pop songs, inspired by the likes of [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]] and [[Taylor Swift]].\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> ''We The Unicorns''{{'}}s Liam Dryden praised the music video for \"Dream\": \"If we weren't hyped for Tessa's upcoming EP \"Halloway\" before now, this video is the ultimate sell.\"<ref name=\"Dryden 2016\" /> Reviewing ''Bad Ideas'' in 2019, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s Hannah Malach described ''Halloway'' as \"dark pop.\"<ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em\n|refs=\n<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\">{{cite web|first1=Gabriel|last1=Aikins|title=Tessa Violet is personally inviting you into her world|work=[[Substream Magazine]]|publisher=Substream Magazine|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2018/08/tessa-violet-interview/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cline 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Jesse|last1=Cline|title=PREMIERE: Tessa Violet Knows \u201cWords Ain\u2019t Enough\u201d on Her Second Album\u2019s Lead Single|work=[[Flood Magazine]]|publisher=Anthemic Agency|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=http://floodmagazine.com/70590/premiere-tessa-violet-knows-words-aint-enough-on-her-second-albums-lead-single/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Annemarie|last1=Cutruzzula|title=EXCLUSIVE: Tessa Violet Talks \u2018Halloway\u2019 EP, Transatlantic Tour, and YouTube|work=CelebMix.com|publisher=CelebMix.com|date=26 October 2016|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://celebmix.com/exclusive-interview-with-tessa-violet/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\">{{cite web|author=Discogs staff|title=Tessa Violet - Halloway (2016, CD)|work=[[Discogs]]|publisher=Zink Media, Inc.|date=|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.discogs.com/Tessa-Violet-Halloway/release/9060210}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dryden 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Liam|last1=Dryden|title=WATCH: Tessa Violet Released The Most Aesthetically Pleasing Music Video Ever|work=We The Unicorns|publisher=Global|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/tessa-violet-music-video-meekakitty/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hull 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Shelton|last1=Hull|title=Tessa Violet takes Florida again, with an Orlando tour date|work=[[Orlando Weekly]]|publisher=[[Euclid Media Group]]|date=14 August 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/orlando/tessa-violet-takes-florida-again-with-an-orlando-tour-date/Content?oid=25825660}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Malach 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Hannah|last1=Malach|title=Tessa Violet Teases New Single 'Games,' Talks 'Wild' Lollapalooza Debut|work=[[Billboard (magazine)]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=25 September 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8529643/tessa-violet-games-new-single-games-lollapalooza-debut}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{YouTube|p=PLFsLD4M4aQvqHkikfmL77wCzVnHC2DmdR|TESSA VIOLET - HALLOWAY EP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halloway}}\n[[Category:2016 EPs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox EP|\n| name         = Halloway\n| type         = EP\n| artist       = [[Tessa Violet]]\n| cover        = Halloway_EP_cover.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = September 16, 2016\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length       = 16:51\n| label        = \n| producer     = Seth Earnest\n| prev_title   = [[Maybe Trapped Mostly Troubled]]\n| prev_year    = 2014\n| next_title   = Bad Ideas\n| next_year    = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Halloway''''' is a 2016 [[Extended play|EP]] by American musician [[Tessa Violet]]. It was released on September 16, 2016 on [[Compact disc|CD]].<ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\" />\n\n== Background ==\nThe title of ''Halloway'' was inspired by the character Will Halloway from the novel ''[[Something Wicked This Way Comes (novel)|Something Wicked This Way Comes]]'' by [[Ray Bradbury]]. Violet listened to [[audiobook]] version while on [[concert tour|tour]] after her mom said it was \"one of the scariest books she\u2019s read, and one of the most well-written.\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> Violet described the album as \"dark pop\".<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n''Halloway'' was released in 2016.<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Hull 2019\" /> Seth Earnest, who has worked with Tessa Violet since 2013, produced the album.<ref name=\"Cline 2019\" /><ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n== Production ==\nDuring ''Halloway''{{'}}s production, Violet listened to [[Taylor Swift]]'s ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]'', [[Troye Sivan]]'s ''[[Blue Neighbourhood]]'', and [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]'s ''[[Badlands (Halsey album)|Badlands]]''; as well as [[pop music|pop]] [[playlist]]s on [[Spotify]].<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n== Alternate versions ==\nViolet released a [[royalty-free]] [[A-side and B-side|B-Side]]s version through her second reward tier of her [[Patreon]].<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = \n| headline        = \n| title1          = Dream\n| length1         = 3:26\n| title2          = Not over You\n| length2         = 3:13\n| title3          = Haze\n| length3         = 3:46\n| title4          = On My Own\n| length4         = 2:56\n| title5          = I Don't Get to Say I Love You Anymore\n| length5         = 3:30\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n''CelebMix.com''{{'}}s Annemarie Cutruzula favoured ''Halloway'' with \"a collection of five fresh pop songs, inspired by the likes of [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]] and [[Taylor Swift]].\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> ''We The Unicorns''{{'}}s Liam Dryden praised the music video for \"Dream\": \"If we weren't hyped for Tessa's upcoming EP \"Halloway\" before now, this video is the ultimate sell.\"<ref name=\"Dryden 2016\" /> Reviewing ''Bad Ideas'' in 2019, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s Hannah Malach described ''Halloway'' as \"dark pop.\"<ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em\n|refs=\n<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\">{{cite web|first1=Gabriel|last1=Aikins|title=Tessa Violet is personally inviting you into her world|work=[[Substream Magazine]]|publisher=Substream Magazine|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2018/08/tessa-violet-interview/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cline 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Jesse|last1=Cline|title=PREMIERE: Tessa Violet Knows \u201cWords Ain\u2019t Enough\u201d on Her Second Album\u2019s Lead Single|work=[[Flood Magazine]]|publisher=Anthemic Agency|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=http://floodmagazine.com/70590/premiere-tessa-violet-knows-words-aint-enough-on-her-second-albums-lead-single/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Annemarie|last1=Cutruzzula|title=EXCLUSIVE: Tessa Violet Talks \u2018Halloway\u2019 EP, Transatlantic Tour, and YouTube|work=CelebMix.com|publisher=CelebMix.com|date=26 October 2016|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://celebmix.com/exclusive-interview-with-tessa-violet/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\">{{cite web|author=Discogs staff|title=Tessa Violet - Halloway (2016, CD)|work=[[Discogs]]|publisher=Zink Media, Inc.|date=|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.discogs.com/Tessa-Violet-Halloway/release/9060210}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Dryden 2016\">{{cite web|first1=Liam|last1=Dryden|title=WATCH: Tessa Violet Released The Most Aesthetically Pleasing Music Video Ever|work=We The Unicorns|publisher=Global|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.wetheunicorns.com/news/tessa-violet-music-video-meekakitty/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hull 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Shelton|last1=Hull|title=Tessa Violet takes Florida again, with an Orlando tour date|work=[[Orlando Weekly]]|publisher=[[Euclid Media Group]]|date=14 August 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/orlando/tessa-violet-takes-florida-again-with-an-orlando-tour-date/Content?oid=25825660}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Malach 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Hannah|last1=Malach|title=Tessa Violet Teases New Single 'Games,' Talks 'Wild' Lollapalooza Debut|work=[[Billboard (magazine)]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=25 September 2019|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8529643/tessa-violet-games-new-single-games-lollapalooza-debut}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{YouTube|p=PLFsLD4M4aQvqHkikfmL77wCzVnHC2DmdR|TESSA VIOLET - HALLOWAY EP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halloway}}\n[[Category:2016 EPs]]\n", "name_user": "DoctorWho42", "label": "safe", "comment": "correcting next_title to \"Bad Ideas (Act One)\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halloway_(EP)"}
{"title_page": "Peachtree Center", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n[[File:Peachtree Center.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Peachtree Center, including the [[Westin Peachtree Plaza Hotel]] (far left) and the [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis]] (far right)]]\n'''Peachtree Center''' is a district located in [[Downtown Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Most of the structures that make up the district were designed by Atlanta architect [[John C. Portman, Jr.]] A defining feature of the Peachtree Center is a network of enclosed pedestrian [[sky bridge]]s suspended above the street-level, which have garnered criticism for discouraging pedestrian street life.<ref>{{cite news | author=Lisa R. Schoolcraft | title=New sky bridge will link Hyatt, Marriott hotels | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2009/10/12/story7.html?page=all | work=Atlanta Business Chronicle | date=October 12, 2009 | accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> The district is served by the [[Peachtree Center (MARTA station)|Peachtree Center]] [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] station, providing access to [[rapid transit]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Skywalk.jpg|thumb|Skywalks are a defining feature of Peachtree Center]]\nIntended to be the new downtown for Atlanta, Peachtree Center emerged as a distinct district in the early 1970s as a networked realm of convention hotels, shopping galleries, and office buildings a quarter-mile north of Five Points. Peachtree Center is notable for its uniform embodiment of the [[Modern architecture|modern]] architectural style popular at the time. Yet the defining feature of Peachtree Center is its insular orientation, which allows patrons and workers to avoid interacting with the street level by traversing the area through sky bridges. By the mid-1980s, Peachtree Center had become the core of a dedicated hotel-convention district that lay at the heart of the Downtown economy, even as the remainder of Downtown Atlanta deteriorated markedly.<ref>{{cite book | last=Low | first=Setha M. | title=Theorizing the City: The New Urban Anthropology Reader | pages=[https://archive.org/details/theorizingcityne0000unse/page/324 324-35] | location=New Brunswick, NJ | publisher=Rutgers University Press | year=1999 | isbn=9780813527192 | url=https://archive.org/details/theorizingcityne0000unse/page/324 }}</ref>\n\nWhile at the time Peachtree Center was considered the salvation of a decaying downtown Atlanta, contemporary city planning is highly critical of such insular environments that \"turn their back\" on the city streets.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | author=Robert M. Craig | publisher=Georgia Institute of Technology | date=14 August 2009 | url=http://www.newgeorgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-1077&hl=y | title=John Portman | encyclopedia=New Georgia Encyclopedia | accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Thus, as intown Atlanta began its post-1990 resurgence, Peachtree Center was increasingly criticized as an area that epitomized contemporary Atlanta's generic urbanity and sense of placelessness.<ref>The Postsouthern Sense Of Place In Contemporary Fiction, Page 6  By Martyn Bone</ref> Other critics claim that Peachtree Center is disorienting, killed downtown street-life, and disregarded the existing urban context.<ref>{{cite conference | author=Mahbub Rashid | title=Revisiting John Portman's Peachtree Center Complex in Atlanta | url=http://www.spacesyntax.net/symposia-archive/SSS1/SpSx%201st%20Symposium%2097%20-2003%20pdf/1st%20Symposium%20Vol%20I%20pdf/4%20-%20Complex%20buildings/17%20Rashid%20300.pdf | conference=Space Syntax First International Symposium | volume=1 | pages=17.1 | year=1997 | location=London | accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe center was recognized for its architecture with listing on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20180323.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2018-03-28|title=WEEKLY LIST OF ACTIONS TAKEN ON PROPERTIES: 3/14/2018 THROUGH 3/26/2018}}</ref>\n==Architecture==\n[[File:AtlantaMarriott-SacredHeart.JPG|thumb|Sacred Heart Catholic Church, located on Peachtree Center Avenue]]\n[[File:Peachtree-center.jpg|thumb|The beige buildings of Peachtree Center]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=250| Name\n! width=100| Height\n! width=70 | Floors\n! width=70 | Year\n!  Notes\n|-\n| [[Peachtree Center Tower]] <br>230 Peachtree Street\n| {{convert|116|m|abbr=on}}\n| 31 floors\n| 1965\n| <ref>{{Emporis|146667|230 Peachtree Building}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|2009|230 Peachtree Building}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peachtree Center North]] (Gas Light Tower)<br>235 Peachtree Street\n| {{convert|101|m|abbr=on}}\n| 27 floors\n| 1968\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121180|Peachtree Center North}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|7077|Peachtree Center North}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peachtree Center South]] <br>225 Peachtree Street\n| {{convert|101|m|abbr=on}}\n| 27 floors\n| 1970\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121097|Peachtree Center South}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|2003|Peachtree Center South}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hyatt Regency Atlanta]]\n| {{convert|104|m|abbr=on}}\n| 24 floors\n| 1967\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121255|Hyatt Regency Atlanta}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|1284|Hyatt Regency Atlanta}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Harris Tower (Atlanta)|Harris Tower]] <br>233 Peachtree Center NE\n| {{convert|116|m|abbr=on}}\n| 31 floors\n| 1974\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121216|Harris Tower}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|1247|Harris Tower}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peachtree Center International Tower]] (Cain Tower)<br>229 Peachtree Street NE\n| {{convert|115|m|abbr=on}}\n| 30 floors\n| 1976\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121179|Peachtree Center International Tower}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|7077|Peachtree Center International Tower}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Marquis I|Marquis ]]One<br>245 Peachtree Center NE\n| {{convert|115|m|abbr=on}}\n| 30 floors\n| 1985\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121152|Marquis I}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|1283|Marquis I}}</ref>\n|- \n| [[Marquis II|Marquis ]]Two<br>285 Peachtree Center NE\n| {{convert|115|m|abbr=on}}\n| 30 floors\n| 1989\n| <ref>{{Emporis|121186|Marquis II}}</ref><ref>{{skyscraperpage|1284|Marquis II}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Peachtree Athletic Club]]<br>227 Courtland Street NE\n| \n| 9 floors\n| 1985\n| <ref>{{Emporis|196744|Harris Tower}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Westin Peachtree Plaza Hotel]]<br>210 Peachtree Street NW\n| {{convert|220.5|m|abbr=on}}\n| 73 floors\n| 1976\n| \n|-\n| [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis]]<br>265 Peachtree Center Avenue NE\n| {{convert|169|m|abbr=on}}\n| 52 floors\n| 1985\n|\n|-\n| [[AmericasMart]]<br>Various Addresses\n| \n| Various Heights\n| 1961, 1979, 1992, 2008\n|\n|-\n| [[SunTrust Plaza]]<br>303 Peachtree Street NE\n| {{convert|265|m|abbr=on}}\n| 60 floors\n| 1992\n|\n|-\n| [[American Cancer Society Center]]<br>250 Williams Street NW\n| \n| 10 floors\n| 1989\n|}\n\n==Economy==\nThe [[U.S. Census Bureau]] has its Atlanta Regional Census Center in Suite 1000 in the Marquis Two Tower.<ref>\"[https://www.census.gov/roatl/www/ The Atlanta Region].\" [[U.S. Census Bureau]]. Retrieved on January 17, 2010.</ref>  Several additional U.S. Government agencies have their southeast regional offices located in the Harris Tower, including the Department of Transportation, Department of Labor, Small Business Administration, and Internal Revenue Service.\n\nThe [[Diplomatic missions of Argentina|Consulate-General of Argentina]] is located in Suite 2101 in the Marquis One Tower.<ref>\"[http://www.consuladoargentinoatlanta.org/contactenos.htm Cont\u00e1ctenos].\" [[Diplomatic missions of Argentina|Consulate-General of Argentina in Atlanta]]. Retrieved on July 28, 2009.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.peachtreecenter.com/pdfs/international_710.pdf Peachtree Center]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\" (Map). Peachtree Center. Retrieved on July 28, 2009.</ref><!--Marquis One Tower = 254 Peachtree Center Avenue--> The [[Diplomatic missions of Germany|Consulate-General of Germany]] is located in Suite 901 of the Marquis Two Tower.<ref>\"[http://www.germany.info/Vertretung/usa/en/03__Consulates/Atlanta/01/__Data.html Address, Contact and Office Hours] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081118153747/http://www.germany.info/Vertretung/usa/en/03__Consulates/Atlanta/01/__Data.html |date=2008-11-18 }}.\" [[Diplomatic missions of Germany|Consulate-General of Germany in Atlanta]]. Retrieved on July 28, 2009.</ref> The [[Diplomatic missions of South Korea|Consulate-General of South Korea]] is located in Suite 500 in the International Tower.<ref>{{cite web | author= | title=About the Mission | url=http://usa-atlanta.mofa.go.kr/english/am/usa-atlanta/main/index.jsp | publisher=Consulate General of the Republic of Korea in Atlanta| date=2013 | accessdate=31 May 2013}} </ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Gallery\n|File:Statues in the SunTrust Plaza.jpg|Public art near SunTrust Plaza\n|File:Peachtree Center MARTA Station.jpg|Peachtree Center MARTA Station\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Embarcadero Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.peachtreecenter.com  Peachtree Center official website]\n{{coord|33.7604|-84.3877|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Atlanta neighborhoods}}\n{{Atlanta landmarks}}\n{{Atlanta shopping}}\n{{Shopping malls in Georgia (U.S. state)}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in the Atlanta metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:John C. Portman Jr. buildings]]\n[[Category:Twin towers]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Fulton County, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n[[File:Peachtree Center.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Peachtree Center, including the [[Westin Peachtree Plaza Hotel]] (far left) and the [[Atlanta Marriott Marquis]] (far right)]]\n'''Peachtree Center''' is a district located in [[Downtown Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. Most of the structures that make up the district were designed by Atlanta architect [[John C. Portman, Jr.]]. A defining feature of the Peachtree Center is a network of enclosed pedestrian [[sky bridge]]s suspended above the street-level, which have garnered criticism for discouraging pedestrian street life.<ref>{{cite news | author=Lisa R. Schoolcraft | title=New sky bridge will link Hyatt, Marriott hotels | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2009/10/12/story7.html?page=all | work=Atlanta Business Chronicle | date=October 12, 2009 | accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> The district is served by the [[Peachtree Center (MARTA station)|Peachtree Center]] [[Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority|MARTA]] station, providing access to [[rapid transit]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Skywalk.jpg|thumb|Skywalks are a defining feature of Peachtree Center]]\nIntended to be the new downtown for Atlanta, Peachtree Center emerged as a distinct district in the early 1970s as a networked realm of convention hotels, shopping galleries, and office buildings a quarter-mile north of Five Points. Peachtree Center is notable for its uniform embodiment of the [[Modern architecture|modern]] architectural style popular at the time. Yet the defining feature of Peachtree Center is its insular orientation, which allows patrons and workers to avoid interacting with the street level by traversing the area through sky bridges. By the mid-1980s, Peachtree Center had become the core of a dedicated hotel-convention district that lay at the heart of the Downtown economy, even as the remainder of Downtown Atlanta deteriorated markedly.<ref>{{cite book | last=Low | first=Setha M. | title=Theorizing the City: The New Urban Anthropology Reader | pages=[https://archive.org/details/theorizingcityne0000unse/page/324 324-35] | location=New Brunswick, NJ | publisher=Rutgers University Press | year=1999 | isbn=9780813527192 | url=https://archive.org/details/theorizingcityne0000unse/page/324 }}</ref>\n\nWhile at the time Peachtree Center was considered the salvation of a decaying downtown Atlanta, contemporary city planning is highly critical of such insular environments that \"turn their back\" on the city streets.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | author=Robert M. Craig | publisher=Georgia Institute of Technology | date=14 August 2009 | url=http://www.newgeorgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-1077&hl=y | title=John Portman | encyclopedia=New Georgia Encyclopedia | accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Thus, as intown Atlanta began its post-1990 resurgence, Peachtree Center was increasingly criticized as an area that epitomized contemporary Atlanta's generic urbanity and sense of placelessness.<ref>The Postsouthern Sense Of Place In Contemporary Fiction, Page 6  By Martyn Bone</ref> Other critics claim that Peachtree Center is disorienting, killed downtown street-life, and disregarded the existing urban context.<ref>{{cite conference | author=Mahbub Rashid | title=Revisiting John Portman's Peachtree Center Complex in Atlanta | url=http://www.spacesyntax.net/symposia-archive/SSS1/SpSx%201st%20Symposium%2097%20-2003%20pdf/1st%20Symposium%20Vol%20I%20pdf/4%20-%20Complex%20buildings/17%20Rashid%20300.pdf | conference=Space Syntax First International Symposium | volume=1 | pages=17.1 | year=1997 | location=London | accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe center was recognized for its architecture with listing on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20180323.htm|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=2018-03-28|title=WEEKLY LIST OF ACTIONS TAKEN ON PROPERTIES: 3/14/2018 THROUGH 3/26/2018}}</ref>\n==Architecture==\n[[File:AtlantaMarriott-SacredHeart.JPG|thumb|Sacred Heart Catholic Church, located on Peachtree Center Avenue]]\n[[File:Peachtree-center.jpg|thumb|The beige buildings of Peachtree Center]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=250| Name\n! width=100| Height\n! width=70 | Floors\n! widt